      "x": "NEONATES. Immature liver and kidney function means slower metabolism and excretion, so drugs act longer — metabolic capacity only approaches adult levels after the first year. Combined with their lower plasma proteins (more free drug) and thinner skin (more complete topical absorption), neonatal dosing is tightly restricted — which is why acetaminophen and ibuprofen are limited or specially dosed below six months. AGING. Normal aging brings reduced liver blood flow, diminished cardiac output, and slower hepatic perfusion, so metabolism slows; reduced renal function slows excretion. Layer on the polypharmacy of older patients — multiple drugs that may induce or inhibit each other's CYP enzymes — and the geriatric patient becomes the hardest to dose. The takeaway is practical: at both age extremes and in hepatic/renal disease, optimize"
