   {
    "id": 6,
    "statement": "agonists and the reasons.",
    "blocks": [
     {
      "t": "q",
      "x": "A patient on a nonselective β-blocker gets epinephrine — why does the blood pressure go the ‘wrong’ way?"
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "OVERVIEW. The contraindications here are receptor logic, not lists — each one is what happens when you block or unmask one arm of a mixed α/β drug. Get the receptor reasoning and you regenerate every one."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "THE UNOPPOSED-α INTERACTION. The classic is nonselective β-blocker + epinephrine. Normally epinephrine’s β₂ vasodilation partly offsets its α₁ vasoconstriction. Block β₂ and that offset disappears, leaving α₁ unopposed → a sharp rise in peripheral resistance and hypertension (often with reflex bradycardia). This is the highest-yield interaction in the lecture and a favorite vignette."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "Clonidine — central α₂ sympatholytic; avoid abrupt discontinuation (rebound hypertension). Uses span hypertension, withdrawal, ADHD."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "Dopamine — dose-dependent (D₁ → β₁ → α₁); MAO inhibitors ↓ its metabolism → ↑ risk of tachycardia/arrhythmia."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "Apraclonidine vs brimonidine — α₂ ocular agents; apraclonidine short-term post-laser, brimonidine more α₂-selective/lipophilic for long-term glaucoma."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "THE OTHER CONTRAINDICATIONS AND INTERACTIONS. Isoproterenol is contraindicated in shock — its β₂ vasodilation worsens hypotension. MAO inhibitors reduce catecholamine metabolism, so co-administration with dopamine, oxymetazoline, or SABAs raises the risk of tachycardia, arrhythmia, and hypertensive responses — a recurring “avoid concomitant use” flag. Clonidine must not be stopped abruptly (rebound hypertension). And inhaled anesthetics sensitize the myocardium to epinephrine, raising arrhythmia risk. Each one traces back to a receptor or a metabolic pathway — reason it out rather than memorizing."
     },
     {
      "t": "cq",
      "x": "Nonselective β-blocker + epinephrine → β₂ vasodilation blocked → unopposed α₁ → hypertension. (unopposed alpha) CQ Isoproterenol contraindicated in shock (β₂ worsens hypotension); MAOIs + sympathomimetics → tachyarrhythmia/HTN. (iso-in-shock / MAOI)"
     },
     {
      "t": "trap",
      "x": "Give epinephrine to someone on a nonselective β-blocker and BP rises (unopposed α₁) — don’t expect the usual mixed response."
     },
     {
      "t": "confusion",
      "x": "Isoproterenol (β₂ vasodilation) is contraindicated in shock; NE/dopamine are the shock pressors — don’t swap them."
     },
     {
      "t": "cue",
      "x": "Patient on an MAOI → avoid adding a sympathomimetic (oxymetazoline, SABA, dopamine) without caution — tachyarrhythmia/HTN risk."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "ReClaude A: Because the nonselective β-blocker abolishes epinephrine’s β₂-mediated vasodilation, leaving its α₁ vasoconstriction unopposed — so peripheral resistance and blood pressure rise instead of showing the usual mixed α/β response."
     }
    ]
   }
