      "t": "p",
      "x": "THE MRSA HANDOFF. Here’s the conceptual punchline and the ReClaude answer: MRSA resistance isn’t about beta-lactamase at all — it’s an altered PBP (PBP2a) that these drugs can’t bind. So a beta-lactamase-resistant penicillin is the wrong tool: there’s no enzyme to outlast, the target itself has changed shape. Resistant (usually nosocomial) staph are covered by vancomycin — which is the thread that carries straight into Lecture 23."
