    "id": 5,
    "statement": "●●○ Penicillin resistance mechanisms, pharmacokinetics, and adverse effects (hypersensitivity)",
    "blocks": [
     {
      "t": "q",
      "x": "A patient reports a penicillin allergy. What is the single most important adverse-effect fact that should shape every subsequent beta-lactam decision in this block?"
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "OVERVIEW. This LO gathers the class-wide facts that apply to all penicillins — how bacteria escape them, how the drugs move through the body, and how they hurt patients. The headline is hypersensitivity, because it reshapes drug choice across the entire beta-lactam family."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "RESISTANCE — four routes. Bacteria defeat penicillins by: (1) beta-lactamase production (chromosomal or plasmid-mediated) that cleaves the ring; (2) altered PBPs the drug can’t bind — this is the MRSA mechanism; (3) decreased permeability / porin changes blocking entry in gram-negatives; and (4) simply lacking a peptidoglycan wall so there’s no target at all. Notice three of these are just the mechanism running in reverse — if you know how the drug works, you can predict how the bug escapes."
     },
     {
      "t": "cq",
      "x": "Four resistance routes: beta-lactamase, altered PBP (MRSA), decreased permeability, no peptidoglycan. (resistance list)"
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "Causes of penicillin resistance: beta-lactamases, altered PBPs (MRSA), decreased permeability, absent peptidoglycan wall."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "Penicillin kinetics: IM depot forms, amoxicillin oral absorption, renal excretion, probenecid blocks secretion, CSF entry only with inflammation."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "Adverse effects: hypersensitivity in 5–25%, Stevens-Johnson in severe cases, ampicillin highest rash incidence; rare anaphylaxis deaths."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "KINETICS. A few class facts: many are given IM (with procaine/benzathine depot forms for sustained levels), amoxicillin has excellent oral absorption, and renal excretion dominates — with probenecid prolonging levels by blocking tubular secretion. Penicillins cross the placenta (no teratogenicity) but only reach the CSF when the meninges are inflamed. And a tidy synergy-with-a-catch: penicillins and aminoglycosides act synergistically but can’t share an IV bag — aminoglycosides are positively charged, penicillins negatively charged, and they inactivate each other."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "ADVERSE EFFECTS — hypersensitivity is the headline. The dominant toxicity is hypersensitivity (5–25%), driven especially by the penicilloic-acid metabolite — ranging from rash to Stevens-Johnson syndrome, with ampicillin carrying the highest rash incidence and rare fatal anaphylaxis. That’s the ReClaude answer: a documented penicillin allergy shapes every downstream choice, including the roughly 5–10% who cross-react to cephalosporins. Other effects: diarrhea, interstitial nephritis, seizures at high levels, platelet dysfunction (the antipseudomonals), and cation toxicity."
     },
     {
      "t": "key",
      "x": "Resistance mirrors mechanism: beta-lactamase, altered PBP (MRSA), low permeability, or no peptidoglycan — derive them, don’t memorize blindly."
     },
     {
      "t": "pearl",
      "x": "Ampicillin = highest rash incidence. Hypersensitivity (penicilloic acid) is the class-defining toxicity and drives cross-reactivity caution with cephalosporins."
     },
     {
      "t": "trap",
      "x": "Never co-infuse a penicillin and an aminoglycoside in the same bag — opposite charges inactivate both, even though they’re synergistic in the patient."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "ReClaude A: Hypersensitivity (5–25%, driven by the penicilloic-acid metabolite, up to Stevens-Johnson and anaphylaxis). A documented penicillin allergy reshapes every later beta-lactam choice, including the ~5–10% cephalosporin cross-reactivity."
     }
    ]
